<DOC><DOCNO> AP901022-0125 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-10-22-90 1757EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-Punjab     10-22 0349</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-Punjab,0414</SECOND><HEAD>Six Student Protestors Slain in Chandigarh</HEAD><BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Assailants in a car shot to death sixstudents on a protest fast and left another person dead and 14injured when they sped away in a blaze of gunfire, police saidMonday.   A police spokesman, who cannot be identified under briefingrules, said the gunmen were suspected Sikh extremists fighting fora separate state in the northern Punjab.   The killings occurred in a downtown market in the state capitalof Chandigarh.   The victims were among a group of upper-caste students sittingunder a tent on a hunger strike to protest federal job quotas thatreserve half of 18 million government jobs for low-castes.   The spokesman said the students were all 17 or younger.   The seventh victim was a street vendor who died when the gunmenfired at onlookers while fleeing, he said. Six of the injured werereported in serious condition.   Immediately after the shooting, a mob set fire to twogovernment-owned buses and hurled stones at a police vehicle.Curfew was imposed and the army arrived to assist police, UnitedNews of India news agency said.   Thousands of students across northern India have been protestingthe job quotas announced Aug. 7 by Prime Minister V.P. Singh. Atleast 67 students have committed suicide in protest and another 67have died in street clashes with police.   Student groups in Punjab were reported to have rejected offersfor help by Sikh extremists.   Earlier Monday, Sikh extremists lured a government patrol downan isolated road and detonated a land mine that killed four policeofficers and wounded 10 others, authorities said.   The three-jeep patrol was headed to Vadalakan village toinvestigate a reported shooting attack by militants on a policepost. The village is 100 miles east of Chandigarh.   No one was injured in the shooting attack on the police post,police said.   Press Trust of India said nine other people were killed in Sikhmilitant violence in the state Monday. It did not give details.   Sikh militants have killed at least 2,439 people this year.   The separatist revolt started in 1983 with Sikh militantsaccusing India's Hindu-dominated government of economic andpolitical discrimination.   Sikhs hold a slim majority over Hindus in Punjab, but accountfor only 2 percent of India's 880 million people while Hindusaccount for 82 percent.</TEXT></DOC>